<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taiwan Prime Minister Arrives in Mexico </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taiwan Prime Minister Arrives in Mexico </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0606081894 Taipei CNA in English 0654 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0606081894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 6 (CNA) -- Premier Lien Chan arrived in 
Mexico from Guatemala early Monday [6 June] morning (Taipei 
time) for a private visit, according to a news release issued by 
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. 
  Lien is visiting Mexico at the invitation of his friend, 
Mario Vazquez, who owns a number of news organizations and 
businesses in the Central American country, the ministry said. 
  Vazquez, who visited Taiwan last year, is very friendly to 
Taiwan and has contributed a lot to promoting substantive 
relations between the Republic of China [ROC] and Mexico, the 
ministry noted. Lien is the highest-ranking ROC official to 
visit Mexico since the two countries severed diplomatic ties in 
1971. 
  While there, the ministry said, Lien will meet with Mexican 
business leaders on Mexico's economic situation since it joined 
the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). 
  Lien may also exchange views with Mexican officials on 
possible investment and economic cooperation projects between 
the two countries and seek Mexico's support for Taiwan's bid to 
join the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, government 
sources said. 
  Taiwan-Mexican trade has increased steadily since 1989 when 
the semi-official China External Trade Development Council 
opened a representative office in Mexico. Two-way trade totaled 
about US $700 million in 1993, with Taiwan enjoying a surplus of 
US $300 million. 
  As a NAFTA member, Mexico provides easy access for foreign 
investors to the vast North American market. Many Taiwan 
companies have set up production facilities in Mexican cities 
bordering the United States in recent years. 
  The ROC opened a representative office in Mexico City on May 
1 to further promote bilateral exchanges. In Taipei, Mexico has 
issued multiple entry visas for Taiwan visitors since June 1991. 
  Lien is being accompanied by his wife and several Foreign 
Ministry officials, including Vice Foreign Minister Fang 
Chin-yen, on his Mexican tour. 
  Lien will leave Mexico Tuesday (Taipei time) for New York 
for 
a family reunion with his two children who are studying there. 
The premier is scheduled to return to Taipei Saturday. 
  Lien, heading a 21-member entourage, flew to El Salvador in 
late May to attend the inauguration of new Salvadoran president, 
Armando Calderon Sol. He then made a four-day official visit to 
Guatemala. Most members of Lien's entourage will not accompany 
Lien to Mexico and the United States. 
  This is Lien's second overseas trip this year, following a 
visit to Honduras and Belize in January. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33360 </DOCNO>
