<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salinas: Mexico Will Not Be `Springboard for Exports' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salinas: Mexico Will Not Be `Springboard for Exports' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0506184294 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0506184294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has said Mexico 
will not be used as a springboard for exports of other nations. 
Investments and production must be in the country. Here is a 
report by Jaime Guerrero. 
  [Begin recording] [Guerrero] For the federal government, 
there is no alternative. Either one invests and produces in 
Mexico or the products of other countries will not be able to 
enter the North American free trade zone. President Salinas 
clearly stated that our country will not be a mere springboard 
for other nations to export to the United States. 
  [Salinas] That is why these investments, especially German 
investments, are taking place now so as to take advantage of 
that opportunity, which the treaty has opened and which in fact 
means more jobs for our fellow countrymen. 
  [Guerrero] The president spoke after inaugurating the first 
industrial complex of auto parts in Puebla. The inauguration 
came during his tour dealing with electricity services. In the 
past six years, the electric power generating capacity increased 
more than 35 percent. This is equivalent to supplying the 
Federal District and Mexico, Nuevo Leon, and Puebla States with 
electricity. In short, electric power service in the country is 
guaranteed. 
  [Salinas] Without sufficient electric power, the foundations 
for additional economic growth for Mexico could not have been 
laid. 
  [Guerrero] Salinas inaugurated the San Lorenzo Almecatla 
electricity substation in Puebla. Afterwards, in Guerrero 
State, he inaugurated the Presidente Plutarco Elias Calles 
thermoelectric plant. It is the biggest in Latin America and 
represents an investment of $2.5 billion. In this tour, 
President Salinas inaugurated three infrastructure projects 
which received investments from three different countries. 
  [Salinas] We do not depend on either a single market or a 
single investor. 
  [Guerrero] The results of this administration in the area of 
electricity service are positive. Twenty-one million Mexicans 
began receiving service and by the end of the government's 
six-year term, 95 percent of the population will have 
electricity. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

