<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Radar Stations Continue To Function </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Radar Stations Continue To Function </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0606035994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network in Spanish 0130 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0606035994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Canal 
A Network </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jorge Ivan Castro from the "AM/PM" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Despite the announcement that Colombia will no 
longer receive information from them, the gringo radars in our 
country are still functioning, and it is not yet known whether 
they will be dismantled. Many questions have been raised 
concerning the issue. 
  According to a bulletin released by the Colombian Air Force, 
the order issued unilaterally on 1 May by the U.S. Defense 
Department called for the suspension of satellite transmissions 
of the information obtained from the radars at the Air Force's 
control center. There has been no mention of plans to dismantle 
the tracking equipment or to continue supplying information to 
the gringo government. 
  A confidential source informed "AM/PM" that the radars are 
still being operated by U.S. personnel and that, in response to 
Colombia's request that the equipment be dismantled, the Defense 
Department requested a deadline of three months when the job can 
be done within a maximum of 10 days. 
  The United States has decided to stop providing Colombia 
with 
information because it believes that Colombia has violated 
several international agreements by ordering attacks on strange 
airplanes, as strange as the gringo military airplanes that 
frequently fly over Colombian territory without permission. 
  An official decision is still expected from the two 
governments with regard to this situation, which is just another 
case of the Gaviria administration's confusing and mysterious 
international policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33391 </DOCNO>
