<H3> <TI>   Minister Downplays IMF, UN, World Bank Advice </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Downplays IMF, UN, World Bank Advice </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0506201994 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
3 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0506201994 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Vicenter Briceno from the "Union Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Central Information Office Minister Guillermo 
Alvarez Bajares today downplayed the suggestion by (Rutillier 
Orloge), adviser to the IMF, the United Nations, and the World 
Bank, that the government freeze prices, salaries, and the 
exchange rate for two months. 
  Alvarez said the expert's recommendation contradicts the 
economic policy of President Rafael Caldera as well as the 
economic policy of private economic organizations, such as the 
Higher Institute of Administration Studies, Iesa, and the 
Venezuelan-American Chamber of Commerce, Venamcham. The adviser 
participated in the forum: "Post-Sosa Plan Alternatives for 
Venezuela," where he said that President Caldera should adopt 
these measures, otherwise, the crisis will deepen and [words 
indistinct] stabilization in a more radical manner. 
  [Begin recording] [Alvarez] That is the center of the 
economic opposition to the current government. It seems that the 
man went [words indistinct] rope at the house of the hanged. 
  [Reporter] [Words indistinct] all economic proposals of.... 
  [Alvarez, interrupting] No, quite the opposite; it disagrees 
with sectors of the private economy. 
  [Reporter] I meant the government's economic policy. 
  [Alvarez] The government's economic policy is absolutely 
independent from what Mr. [name indistinct], the IMF, Venamcham, 
and Iesa might say. Absolutely different. 
  [Reporter] [Words indistinct] break from IMF? 
  [Alvarez] No, perhaps a break between the IMF and Iesa and 
Venamcham. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

