<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turks and Caicos Islands Agree To Receive Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turks and Caicos Islands Agree To Receive Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0606233094 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1600 
GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0606233094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Turks and Caicos Islands have agreed to 
temporarily receive Haitian refugees. After Jamaica, it will be 
the turn of the Turks and Caicos Islands to accept the Haitian 
boat people on their territory for questioning by the U.S. Coast 
Guard. This decision was made by the local government of the 
Turks and Caicos Islands, a British colony located 90 miles off 
Haiti. Rothschild Francois has details: 
  [Begin Francois recording] In the agreement concluded 
between 
Washington and the Turks and Caicos Island Government, it was 
mentioned that the United States will provide facilities for the 
questioning of Haitian refugees while they are being considered 
for political asylum in the United States. These installations 
will include the utilization of a desalinization factory, the 
extension of the wharf to accommodate the landing of U.S. ships, 
and the building of a landing runway. The United States will pay 
all expenses for this operation and will also provide aid to the 
Turks and Caicos Islands. One to two million dollars will be 
spent for this program. The first U.S. technicians are expected 
on the island within the coming days to prepare for the 
launching of this program, which will be using a staff of 250. 
  According to the Press Society, the agreement between the 
Turks and Caicos Islands and the United States indicates that 
before the center for refugees is operational, the United States 
could begin interviewing the Haitian boat people on board a U.S. 
ship in the waters of Turk Island, more precisely, near Grand 
Turk. 
  Since the announcement of this partial change in the U.S. 
policy regarding Haitian refugees, more than 1,500 refugees have 
been repatriated to Port-au-Prince. The new U.S. policy has not 
yet been applied. This policy provides that Haitian refugees 
will no longer be sent back directly to Port-au-Prince, but will 
be questioned aboard U.S. ships. The qualified refugees who 
receive political asylum could be admitted to the U.S. 
territory, while other boat people would be repatriated to 
Port-au-Prince by the U.S. Coast Guard. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

