<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   CNEA Wants Activities Grouped in State Company </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CNEA Wants Activities Grouped in State Company </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0206182894 Buenos Aires LA NACION in Spanish 1 Jun 94 
Section 2 p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0206182894 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA NACION </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Manuel Mondino, president of the National Atomic 
Energy Commission (CNEA), has proposed that the organization's 
productive activities be turned into an incorporated state 
enterprise that will be able to quote its shares on the stock 
market. 
  "We have reached a stage in which the CNEA, which was born 
as 
a series of laboratories, has ended up creating a prolific 
industrial activity that must be broken down into component 
parts," Mondino said. 
  "The state tasks that cannot be delegated must remain within 
the state and the productive components must be overseen by a 
state incorporated company. The key is to maintain the 
laboratory-factory unity," the CNEA chief added during the 
commemoration of the organization's 44th anniversary. 
  The proposal to quote shares on the stock market, although 
Mondino did not go into details, still must be approved by the 
government. The CNEA and the Energy Secretariat still do not 
have a common position on how to undertake the privatization of 
nuclear activity, the only one that remains in the hands of the 
state since the energy market's deregulation began two years ago. 
  But the CNEA Association of Professionals has demanded the 
sanctioning of a law that will regulate nuclear activities. 
  The organization recalled that "the most advanced countries 
consider energy a strategic asset." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

