<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Continue Over Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Continue Over Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0606200194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1516 GMT 6 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0606200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Javier Rodriguez] </F>
  [Text] Havana, 6 Jun (PL) -- Nine days after they 
forcefully entered the Belgian ambassador's residence in Havana, 
the group of occupants continue defying the Cuban and Belgian 
governments' opposition to their stay in the building. 
  Foreign Ministry sources confirmed today to PRENSA LATINA 
that normal conversations continue between Belgian diplomats and 
local foreign ministry officials in a daily analysis of the 
situation and of the mechanisms to apply for attaining a 
definite solution to the issue. 
  Willy Verriest, special envoy from Brussels, and Paul 
Vermkirsch, chief of the Belgian mission in Cuba, have already 
met twice with acting Foreign Minister Isabel Allende. They 
also exchanged viewpoints with Serafin Rodriguez, chief of the 
Europe Department. 
  In all cases, the parties agree on recognizing the illegal 
nature of the stay by the group occupying the Belgian residence, 
which violates the security and extra territoriality of this 
European nation's legation in the Caribbean island. 
  Likewise, the parties ratified the Cuban Government's 
refusal 
to recognize this type of action as a valid method to leave the 
country, as it ignores the legal procedures established for 
these cases. 
  The sources reaffirmed that as a show of good will, Cuba 
will 
abstain from taking measures against those who voluntarily leave 
the ambassador's residence and decide -- if they so wish -- to 
process in an appropriate manner their request to travel abroad. 
  This measure [words indistinct] was confirmed by the recent 
departure of four occupants and their return, without any 
difficulty, to their respective homes. 
  Foreign reporters and observers who reside in Havana feel 
that this attitude by the other occupants of ignoring the joint 
stand of Cuba and Belgium regarding their irregular presence in 
the residence keeps them isolated, and it is deliberately 
hindering a solution to the problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

