<H3> <TI>   Ibero-American Summit To Stress Science, Technology </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ibero-American Summit To Stress Science, Technology </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0506040794 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1608 GMT 4 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0506040794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Abel Sardina] </F>
  [Text] Cartagena de Indias, 4 Jun (PL) -- Directors of 
scientific activities from 17 countries meeting here urged 
Ibero-American rulers to reinforce investment to "consolidate 
scientific and technological capacities." 
  Following three days of debate in this Colombian city, 
participants think that scientific-technical consolidation is 
essential "due to the impact it has on improving competitiveness 
and employment in our economies, as well as the well-being of 
our society." 
  The conference on sustained financing for technological 
investigation and development in Ibero-America approved the 
conclusions the previous day. These will be handed to the heads 
of state and government of Spain, Portugal, and the 19 countries 
of Iberic origin, which will meet here 14-15 June. 
  "Sustained growth in public investment in innovation must be 
reinforced in order to consolidate the incipient modernization 
processes of the productive apparatus and to induce businesses 
to participate in the financing of these activities," the 
recommendations state, according to what was learned today by 
PRENSA LATINA. 
  The directors of scientific, technological, and 
investigative 
activities also think that "the decisive participation of the 
three multilateral credit organizations is essential." 
Likewise, they recommended persisting in investigative and 
development efforts, "despite the macroeconomic limitations 
imposed by pressing social priorities." To this end they argued 
that, if this is not done, "the region's project to remain 
competitive in world trade and to use science to improve the 
people's conditions, can be seriously compromised." 
  A press communique on the talks recognized Cuba's effort in 
training masses of professionals and investigators in basic 
sectors as "a notable example of what is sought" in this field. 
  Cuba's Dr. Rosa Elena Simeon, minister of science, 
technology, and environment, speaking with PRENSA LATINA, thinks 
that Latin American countries do not have the 
technical-scientific base required to enter the free competition 
imposed by free trade and the GATT [General Agreement on Tariffs 
and Trade] agreements. 
  The meeting also had representatives from Argentina, 
Bolivia, 
Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Costa Rica, Spain, Guatemala, Honduras, 
Mexico, Nicaragua, Panama, Peru, Uruguay, Portugal, and 
Venezuela. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

