<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Miami Summit Seen as Plan To Discredit Ibero-America </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Miami Summit Seen as Plan To Discredit Ibero-America </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0606015394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1240 GMT 4 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0606015394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 4 Jun (PL) -- The newspaper GRANMA today 
published a commentary on the upcoming Ibero-American Summit, 
describing it as a challenge and a commitment for participants. 
The summit is scheduled to begin on Tuesday in Cartagena de 
Indias, Colombia. 
  GRANMA, the official newspaper of the Central Committee of 
the Communist Party of Cuba, pointed out that the time has come 
to efficiently and independently revive, reaffirm, and establish 
in concrete the course Ibero-America must follow. 
  The newspaper underscored the fact that the conference will 
be held as a result of the U.S. Government's call for another 
presidential summit, which will be held in Miami in December, 
for the purpose of attacking, discrediting, and overshadowing 
the results of the Ibero-American movement that is under way. 
  This situation creates for the presidents the undeniable 
need 
to reach a clear and definitive commitment in Cartagena that 
will strengthen the community of Ibero-American nations and 
establish a specific integration program, GRANMA said. Further 
on, the commentary stated that this commitment is the only way 
the countries attending the Miami summit can arrive as a group 
that shares strong bonds and common goals. 
  GRANMA said that in Cartagena the presidents will not be 
able 
to avoid the issue of the U.S. economic and trade blockade 
against Cuba, including the Torricelli Law, regarding which a 
statement was issued at the past summit and two resolutions have 
been issued by the UN General Assembly. 
  The commentary emphasizes that Cuba participates in these 
forums with the moral and political authority it draws from its 
huge efforts and social projects, which have achieved goals 
which, for many, still constitute dreams or hopes and its proven 
desire for integration. 
  Ibero-America knows, the newspaper underscored, that our 
country is an unyielding champion of principles, such as 
nonintervention, sovereignty, and self-determination, which are 
not only deeply rooted but legally established and universally 
accepted in international relations. The Ibero-American 
countries, the commentary concludes, will once again have an 
opportunity to examine urgent regional problems and the effects 
and consequences that other worldwide problems have on this part 
of the world, because, for them, this fourth summit is their 
summit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

