<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   SELA Resolution Rejects Embargo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SELA Resolution Rejects Embargo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0506225794 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2055 GMT 3 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0506225794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 3 Jun (PL) -- The 20th Council of the 
Latin American Economic System (SELA) today approved a 
resolution rejecting the U.S.-imposed economic, trade, and 
financial blockade instituted against Cuba more than three 
decades ago. The document, which was studied by 
ministerial-level delegations, recognizes the importance of 
reaffirming the sovereignty of the region's countries and says 
in its text: 
  "The need to put an end to the U.S.-imposed economic, trade, 
and financial blockade against Cuba. [sentence as received] 
  "In view of paragraphs A and B of articles 3 and 4 and 
paragraphs 1 and 4 of article 5 of the Panama Agreement and 
considering resolution No. 112 regarding the `imposition of 
coercive economic measures' and resolutions 47/19 and 40/16 of 
the UN General Assembly, entitled `The Need To End The 
U.S.-Imposed Economic, Trade, and Financial Blockade Against 
Cuba'; 
  "Whereas, there is the need to reaffirm, among other 
principles, the sovereign equality of states, nonintervention in 
their internal affairs, and the freedom of international trade 
and navigation recognized in numerous international legal 
instruments; 
  "Whereas, free trade is an element that contributes to the 
people's economic development and well-being; and 
  "Whereas, there is the need to boost trade relations in the 
American hemisphere, in adherence to the principle of free trade 
and navigation. 
  "The Latin American Council resolves to reject the 
application of unilateral measures that affect free development 
of international commerce and contravene principles of 
international law. To this end, the Council urges the lifting 
of the economic, trade, and financial blockade against Cuba and 
expresses support for UN General Assembly resolution 48/16, 
which demands the elimination of unilateral actions that are 
incongruent with the international economic and political 
context." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

