<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Tighten Security Near Diplomatic Missions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Tighten Security Near Diplomatic Missions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0706015094 Paris AFP in Spanish 0048 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0706015094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 6 Jun (AFP) -- The Cuban Police have 
tightened security around several diplomatic missions and 
residences in Havana, while 124 Cubans continue to occupy the 
residence of the Belgian ambassador hoping to obtain political 
asylum. 
  Security has been beefed up, particularly around the 
Argentine Embassy, some 100 meters from the Belgian residence, 
in Miramar District (western Havana). A special brigade truck 
and two patrol vehicles are blocking the street by the mission. 
Also, dozens of security guards, some armed with AK-47 rifles, 
were seen guarding the area for the first time since the 
beginning of the crisis. The intense deployment apparently is 
due to rumors of the imminent departure of would-be emigres to 
Argentine diplomatic missions. 
  The situation appeared to be at a standstill in the Belgian 
residence, which has been occupied for 10 days by 68 men, 32 
women, and 24 children. Belgian and Cuban representatives have 
been in daily contact, while Belgian special envoy Willy 
Verriest is intent on trying to convince the refugees to leave 
the building. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

