<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Salutes Minint Anniversary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Salutes Minint Anniversary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0606163794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish GMT 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL0606163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Our Opinion" commentary by Orlando Contreras from the </F>
"Doing Radio" newscast] 
  [Text] The 33d anniversary of the founding of the Interior 
Ministry [Minint] is being celebrated today. The "Doing Radio" 
newscast sends all its self-sacrificing fighters its most 
fraternal greetings. 
  The revolution has waged a constant struggle against those 
who have tried to crush the achievements of this process 
throughout three decades; and, within that struggle, the Minint 
fighters have played a role that deserves full recognition. 
Tasks which deal with the prevention of crime and repression of 
activities which conspire against the security, integrity, and 
assets of the people and the citizens represent difficult, 
self-sacrificing work that entails sacrifices, total dedication, 
and -- many times -- serious risks because many Minint fighters 
have lost their lives in the line of duty. 
  These tasks require honest men because nothing is more 
damaging than the abuse of power or the use of that authority 
with intentions other than those granted by the revolution and 
the law to the organizations and the men who serve it. Minint 
fighters have achieved success in their tasks because they have 
had the people's full support. In a revolution like ours, the 
repression of criminal activities, whatever their nature, always 
has the people's support. This is one of the keys of the Minint 
fighters' success in their various activities. 
  Today, when we mark the foundation of the Minint, which was 
formed with a nucleus of men from the rebel army and clandestine 
groups, "Doing Radio" joins the people in greeting those 
fighters with strong principles, convictions, and determination 
to serve the people, which is the source of their authority. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

