<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polls Predict Fujimori, Perez de Cuellar Tie </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Polls Predict Fujimori, Perez de Cuellar Tie </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0606182094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1902 GMT 5 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0606182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 5 Jun (EFE) -- An opinion poll that was 
released in Lima on 5 June shows that Peruvian President Alberto 
Fujimori and former UN Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar 
would tie at presidential runoff elections if they were held 
right now. 
  The metropolitan daily EXPRESO published the results of the 
opinion poll conducted by Datum, a private company. The poll 
shows that in the event of runoff elections, and should Fujimori 
and Perez de Cuellar run for president, Fujimori would get 43.8 
percent of the votes and Perez de Cuellar would get 42.8 
percent. Datum feels that "technically" these figures should be 
considered a "tie." 
  The opinion poll shows that during the first electoral round 
neither candidate would obtain 50 percent plus one vote. The 
current president would get 39.9 percent and the former UN 
secretary general would get 32.2 percent. 
  Peruvian presidential and legislative elections are 
scheduled 
for April 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

