<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   OAS Meeting Opens, Discusses Intervention in Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS Meeting Opens, Discusses Intervention in Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    OAS Resolution Opens Door to Intervention </H4>

<F P=102> PA0706203994 Paris AFP in Spanish 2004 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0706203994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belem do Para, 7 June (AFP) -- The 34 countries of 
the OAS approved a resolution on Tuesday that leaves the door 
open for a future armed intervention in Haiti. 
  The foreign ministers approved the resolution, the product 
of 
long hours of negotiations, within the framework of the General 
Assembly that has met since Monday in Belem do Para, Brazil. 
The matter that extended the private negotiations, according to 
diplomats who participated, dealt with the insistence by some 
countries that the new actions that are endorsed in a general 
manner in the last paragraph of the preamble of the draft 
resolution be limited to the "peaceful" area. In the final 
version of the draft seen by the foreign ministers, this 
limitation was left out of the text. 
  The above-mentioned paragraph takes into account "the 
relevancy for the members to strengthen the necessary political 
and diplomatic actions to bring about a lasting solution to the 
Haitian crisis within the framework of the OAS Charter and 
international law." 
  "It is a triumph for the United States because, although it 
does not endorse or even mention an intervention, it does not 
exclude it either," a diplomat who spoke on condition of 
anonymity told AFP. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

