<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panama Addresses OAS Assembly on Canal Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panama Addresses OAS Assembly on Canal Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0806021994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2259 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0806021994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belem do Para, 7 Jun (EFE) -- Panamanian Vice 
Foreign Minister Carlos Cordero stated here today that the 
Panamanian Government will not accept "the slightest change" in 
the terms and timetable established in the Torrijos-Carter 
treaty for the handover of the Panama Canal to Panama. 
  Cordero emphasized the significance of faithfully complying 
with the accords signed in 1977 by Panama and the United States, 
which sought to decolonize Panama. He added that the canal 
"must come under absolute Panamanian domain and sovereignty." 
  Today, Cordero addressed the 24th OAS General Assembly, 
which 
opened on 6 June at the city of Belem, Para State, in the 
Brazilian Amazon region. The assembly is due to close on 10 
June. 
  Cordero noted the interest of President Guillermo Endara's 
government in promoting a constitutional reform that would 
guarantee a professional administration of the Panama Canal as 
soon as it comes under complete Panamanian jurisdiction five 
years from now. 
  Cordero added that a professional administration, through an 
autonomous organization, would prevent the canal from being 
affected by political ups and downs and will reassure its 
customers around the world. 
  Cordero also outlined a number of international agreements 
to 
fight drug trafficking signed by Panama with the United States, 
Great Britain, Central American countries, Colombia, and the 
United Nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

