<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chile To Join Mercosur as `Associate' Member </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chile To Join Mercosur as `Associate' Member </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0706145394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2114 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0706145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belem, Para (Brazil), 6 Jun (EFE) -- On 6 June, 
Chilean Foreign Minister Carlos Figueroa told EFE NEWS AGENCY 
that Chile will establish a free trade zone with the Common 
Market of the South (Mercosur), composed of Argentina, Brazil, 
Paraguay, and Uruguay, within 10 years, at the very most. 
  Figueroa added that the Chilean Government will formalize 
its 
proposal in a document to be submitted to Argentine Foreign 
Minister Guido Di Tella, who is also Mercosur Council chairman, 
on 8 June. 
  The Chilean foreign minister is participating in the 24th 
OAS 
General Assembly, which was inaugurated in Belem, a city in Para 
State's Amazon region, on 6 June and will continue its 
deliberations until 10 June. 
  Figueroa noted: "We have not joined Mercosur due to 
difficulties arising from import duties." 
  Chile levies an 11 percent tariff on all imports regardless 
of the country of origin, whereas Mercosur member countries levy 
higher tariffs, the rate of which varies according to products. 
  After a meeting with Mercosur foreign ministers in Belem, 
Minister Figueroa announced on 5 June that Chile will join 
Mercosur as an associate rather than full member. He 
nonetheless did not rule out the possibility of his country 
joining Mercosur in the future. 
  Chile is one of the Latin American countries with the 
highest 
growth rate and the largest volume of foreign trade. It is the 
only country in the region that has not joined any integration 
movements in South America like Mercosur, the Andean Group, and 
the Amazon Pact. 
  Figueroa said this decision will not produce changes in the 
negotiations his country is undertaking with the United States, 
the main partner of NAFTA, which also comprises Canada and 
Mexico. 
  The foreign minister added that the Treaty of Asuncion 
allows 
"any country" that does not belong to other economic blocs "to 
join" Mercosur. 
  Mercosur was established in March 1991 by Argentina, Brazil, 
Paraguay, and Uruguay. These countries had invited Chile to 
join Mercosur since its inception but to no avail. At that 
time, Chilean authorities contended that they would rather not 
join this integration movement since Chile's import duties were 
lower than those of its neighbors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-33535 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat110bb_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-110 </AU>
