<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   60,000 Protest Alleged Electoral Fraud </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    60,000 Protest Alleged Electoral Fraud </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806033494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2359 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0806033494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 7 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- Police sources 
report that approximately 60,000 Dominicans protested today in 
Cotuy, 140 km northeast of Santo Domingo, against the fraud 
allegedly perpetrated in the 16 May general elections. 
  Several civic organizations in Cotuy called residents to a 
general work stoppage -- the first of several protest actions 
planned by the Dominican opposition and in which more than 50 
percent of the population participated. 
  According to reports, public transportation was scarce and 
only a few stores conducted normal operations during the strike. 
Nevertheless, no serious incidents were reported. 
  Reports of serious irregularities during the elections have 
delayed the proclamation of a new president. 
  Jose Francisco Pena Gomez, presidential candidate of the 
opposition Dominican Revolutionary Party, today threatened to 
call a general strike if current President Joaquin Balaguer is 
proclaimed the winner. 
  Pena Gomez declared: "The illegal proclamation of Balaguer 
would unleash all kinds of protests, including a general strike. 
It would not be necessary, however, to resort to violence. 
Peaceful resistance would suffice." He added, "We will 
paralyze entire cities and provinces." 
  Pena Gomez has repeatedly claimed that the Central Electoral 
Board permitted "a colossal and blatant fraud" in the May 
elections in the Dominican Republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

