<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jonassaint Government Protests Clinton Remark </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jonassaint Government Protests Clinton Remark </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0706182294 Paris AFP in Spanish 1648 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0706182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 7 Jun (AFP) -- The government of 
provisional Haitian President Emile Jonassaint (not recognized 
by the international community) protested "vigorously" today 
against a statement by U.S. President Bill Clinton that Haiti is 
located in the U.S. "backyard." 
  "Untimely statements such as this violate the cardinal and 
universal principles of sovereignty and self-determination that 
govern relations among nations," a communique issued by the 
provisional government pointed out. "The sacred land of Haiti 
is not and will never be the backyard of any other state, not 
even of the world's most powerful," the document added. 
  After reminding that the use of force remains among the U.S. 
options for restoring democracy in Haiti, Clinton pointed out on 
19 May, the United States has "significant interests" in this 
country, which is located "in the backyard" of the United 
States. He also commented on the problem of the Haitian refugees 
and on drug trafficking. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

