<DOCNO> FBIS4-33560 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat110_c_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-110 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0706233494 </F>
<F P=103> PA0706233494 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 7 June. 
  The Mexican economy grew slightly in the first quarter with 
the GDP increasing 0.5 percent over the same period in 1993. 
Nevertheless, for thousands of Mexican companies and their 
employees, the recession that began in 1993 continued. This was 
particularly true in the service subsectors of trade, 
restaurants, and hotels. The recession in the service sector 
has lasted longer than in the other areas of the economy. The 
last time this sector showed growth was in the first quarter of 
1993, when it registered an annual growth rate of 2.2 percent. 
(Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network in Spanish 1300 
GMT 2 Jun 94) 
  CORPAMEX [Mexican Employers Confederation] President Antonio 
Sanchez Diaz de Rivera told UNOMASUNO yesterday that economic 
growth has been "delayed" and that its reactivation will not be 
seen until 1995. In a news conference, Diaz proposed that new 
family businesses be exempt from all types of taxes and a 3 
percent cap be placed on sales taxes. According to Diaz, these 
measures will allow "groups in the underground economy to pass 
into the formal economy, and this will prevent the unemployment 
problem from worsening." (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 1 Jun 
94 pp 1, 19) 
  The under secretary of trade has said NAFTA is "progressing 
very well," adding that proof of this is that manufacturing 
exports in the first quarter rose 25.4 percent over the same 
period last year. The under secretary also announced that a free 
trade agreement will be signed among the G-3 nations -- 
Colombia, Mexico, and Venezuela -- during the upcoming 
Ibero-American presidential summit in Cartagena de Indias, 
Colombia. The official also said the free trade agreement 
signed with Costa Rica has paved the way for negotiations with 
Nicaragua, Guatemala, Honduras, and El Salvador. (Mexico City 
NOTIMEX in Spanish 2024 GMT 2 Jun 94) 
  The Bancomer Financial Group has announced that the lifting 
of trade barriers and lagging technology have had an adverse 
effect on the Mexican textile industry, even though in the 
long-run this could be the one of the sectors to benefit most 
from NAFTA. The Bancomer Group forecasts a 3.9 percent increase 
in the GDP this year, but only a 2.1 percent increase in the 
garment industry's gross product. Problems faced by the industry 
include a lack of integration in terms of production, a shortage 
of raw materials, low quality, limited designs, and high 
financing costs. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 2 Jun 94 p 17) 
  A poll conducted by the Secretariat of Commerce and 
Industrial Development (SECOFI) among industrialists, asking 
whether it should move to expedite the liberalization of trade 
barriers on some products listed under NAFTA, has met with a 
very poor response, while most respondents announced their 
opposition to the expediting of liberalization. The industrial 
sectors voicing the greatest opposition were those that produce 
glass, wine, household appliances, pharmaceuticals, heavy 
machinery, and chemicals. Meanwhile, industries in favor of 
speeding up the lifting of trade barriers were those that 
produce shoes, textiles, citrus fruits, flowers, and tropical 
fruits. (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 2 Jun 94 p 49) 
  The president of the National Agrarian Council has said 
problems still remain six months after NAFTA's implementation, 
particularly in terms of customs and the overall understanding 
of the trilateral agreement's terminology. The president noted 
that the majority of producers in this sector have expressed 
their opposition to speeding up the lifting of tariffs. 
Nevertheless, it was reported that the sector grew 7 percent in 
the first quarter, mainly because of strong exports of coffee 
and cattle. (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 2 Jun 94 p 52) 
  The governments of Mexico and the UK yesterday signed an 
agreement on tax issues. The agreement is aimed at averting 
double taxation and tax evasion on income and capital gains. 
The agreement seeks to eliminate excessive taxes resulting in 
double taxation on investments and capital flow between the two 
nations. The agreement also makes it easier for tax authorities 
from both nations to exchange information to combat fraud and 
tax evasion. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 3 Jun 94 p 14) 
  Japanese businessmen said during a meeting with President 
Carlos Salinas de Gortari that Japanese companies in the 
electric, banking, automobile, heavy machinery, construction, 
and food industries are interested in investing in Mexico in 
light of the nation's secure economic future. Among the 
companies interested in investing are: Bank of Tokyo, Honda 
Motors, Canon Ltd., Sanyo, Nissan, Clarion, Aoki Corp., Marubeni 
Corp., and Terumo. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0333 GMT 1 
Jun 94) 
  Yesterday, Mexican Petroleum [PEMEX] announced a 25-50 cent 
increase in the per-barrel price of petroleum as of 1 June for 
oil sales to the Americas, Europe, and the Far East. The 
measure is designed to keep Mexican crude aligned with prices on 
the international market. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 1 
Jun 94 p 18) 
  PEMEX Gas Company and Basic Petrochemical Company -- PEMEX 
subsidiaries -- showed a 444 million new peso gross profit for 
the first quarter of 1994. In a press release, state-owned 
PEMEX reported that with larger revenues mainly from sales and a 
reduction in expenditures, the operation and investment budget 
showed a 570 million new peso surplus as opposed to the budgeted 
deficit of about 110 million new pesos. (Mexico City LA JORNADA 
in Spanish 6 Jun 94 p 48) 
  SECOFI will apply, as of Saturday, a retaliatory quota of 
45.74 percent on beef imports from the EU. SECOFI also reported 
that an "antidumping" investigation has been initiated into beef 
imports from the United States. The retaliatory quota was 
imposed on meat from the EU after it was confirmed that European 
nations still subsidize this sector. If the investigations into 
the U.S. imports demonstrate questionable trade practices, a 
retaliatory quota will also be imposed on these imports. (Mexico 
City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1651 GMT 3 Jun 94) 
  The public sector, banking sector, and private industry's 
increase in contracting net international debts has prompted 
considerable growth in Mexico's overall foreign debt in the 
first quarter. According to SECOFI and the Bank of Mexico, 
foreign debt reached an all-time high in March at $119.179 
billion. That is 6.7 percent higher than accumulated debt 
recorded in December 1993. Most foreign funds were used to 
finance export projects, as well as small and medium-sized 
businesses. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 6 Jun 94 p 3A) 
  During 1993, private foreign debt increased by $10.791 
billion, of which 67.8 percent was incurred by the nonfinancial 
sector and 32.2 percent by the banking sector. After the 
renegotiation of government liabilities in 1990, the placing of 
bonds and securities became the main foreign financing tool for 
a total of $5.285 billion in 1993. Of this total, 73.6 percent 
corresponds to 44 emissions by nonbanking firms and 26.4 percent 
to six emissions by the banking sector. (Mexico City EL 
FINANCIERO in Spanish 6 Jun 94 pp 1, 10) 
  SECOFI confirmed that in the first 1994 quarter, 19 percent 
of the 41.4 billion new pesos earmarked for public investments 
in 1994 had already been invested in public agencies and 
corporations. The total investment budget was increased by 
7.324 billion new pesos to include investments in the National 
Solidarity program. The Group of Economists and Associates 
indicated that for the first time in several years public 
savings was not enough to finance public investments. (Mexico 
City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 6 Jun 94 p 7) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

