<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806011694 </F>
<F P=103> PA0806011694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Salvadoran economic developments monitored through 7 
Jun. 
  Addressing a meeting of presidents from the Central American 
Chambers of Commerce, Economy Minister Luis Enrique Cordova on 2 
June warned that if equitable treatment is not guaranteed in 
free trade negotiations, there is a risk that investments will 
be diverted away from Central America. The meeting is being 
held before negotiations for a free trade treaty with Mexico to 
review the private sector's role in the negotiations. (San 
Salvador Canal Doce Television in Spanish 0300 GMT 3 Jun 94) 
  The Central Bank reported on 3 June that economic activity 
in 
El Salvador increased 7.1 percent during the first three months 
of 1994. The increase was primarily attributed to the "dynamic" 
output of the industrial and construction sectors. The 1994 
monetary program is designed to achieve overall economic growth 
of 5-6 percent. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2113 GMT 3 Jun 94) 

</TEXT>

