<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806005394 </F>
<F P=103> PA0806005394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Guatemalan economic developments monitored through 7 
June. 
  The Guatemalan Congress has refrained from approving the 
renegotiation of the country's debt with the Paris Club. This 
decision places the country in a precarious position and could 
even close the doors to future international loans. Guatemalan 
Christian Democracy and Solidarity Action Movement deputies 
blocked a proposal in favor of the renegotiation. (Guatemala 
City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 1 Jun 94 p 79) 
  The Central Bank of Guatemala has reported that between 
January and May 1994 the country's foreign exchange income rose 
by 18.7 percent. The country's foreign trade contributed 
greatly to this increase. Sales of traditional products 
increased 26.5 percent, despite declines in cotton and banana 
sales. Meanwhile, sales of nontraditional products increased 
14.4 percent. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0256 GMT 7 Jun 94) 
  Finance Minister Ana Ordonez has reported that during the 
first trimester of the year, Guatemala's fiscal deficit 
increased by some $52.2 million. The minister said the fact 
that taxpayers failed to pay taxes on time contributed to the 
shortfall. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1841 GMT 3 Jun 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

