<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806004294 </F>
<F P=103> PA0806004294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Honduran economic developments monitored through 7 
June. 
  Finance Minister Juan Ferrera has announced that to fulfill 
the international financial organizations' requirement to reduce 
the fiscal deficit from 11 percent to 5 percent, the government 
still needs to make an adjustment of some 1.5 billion lempiras. 
Meanwhile, Minister Ferrera explained that the Honduran 
Government will not eliminate subsidies on transportation or on 
the price of kerosene. (Tegucigalpa EL PERIODICO DE HONDURAS in 
Spanish 31 May 94 p 11) 
  The government collected 1 billion lempiras in taxes in the 
first five months of the year, according to Deputy Finance 
Minister Ramiro Lozano Landa. He added that tax revenues were 
300 million lempiras higher than in the same period in 1993. 
Nevertheless, Lozano Landa pointed out that the increased 
revenues still need to be accompanied by a 10 percent reduction 
in government spending, as recently noted by Hugo Neo Pino, 
president of the Central Bank of Honduras (BCH). (San Pedro Sula 
TIEMPO in Spanish 1 Jun 94 p 6) 
  According to a report issued by the Economic Studies 
Department of the BCH, inflation reached 12.7 percent in the 
first five months of the year. The BCH report added that, if 
the growth rate continues at its current pace, the government 
will not be able to meet its goal of an 18-percent rate of 
inflation by the end of 1994. (Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA in Spanish 
3 Jun 94 p 13) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

