<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806004194 </F>
<F P=103> PA0806004194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Panamanian economic developments monitored through 7 
June. 
  Eduardo Linares, deputy minister of planning and economic 
policy, has reported that international financial institutes 
(IFI's) could "withhold approximately $300 million in credits if 
the government fails to comply with various stringent conditions 
imposed by these organizations." He added, "There would be a 
$1.9 million deficit in 1994 budget if this money is withheld." 
The government is expected to make several modifications to the 
national budget to prevent the IFI's decision from negatively 
affecting the budget. Planning Minister Delia Cardenas, Finance 
Minister Victor Juliao, and Comptroller General Jose Chen Barria 
are scheduled to meet on 6 June to discuss the issue. (Panama 
City LA PRENSA in Spanish 1 Jun 94 p 1A) 
  A report issued by the Economic Commission for Latin America 
shows that the Central American region registered an economic 
growth rate of more than 4 percent in 1993, "which has generated 
a moderate increase in the domestic GNP of each nation of the 
region for the second year in a row." The report adds that 
Central America "advanced in its goal of controlling inflation, 
which in Costa Rica decreased from 17 percent to 9 percent, and 
in Guatemala from 14 percent to 12 percent. In Honduras and 
Nicaragua, however, inflation increased to 15 percent and 25 
percent, respectively." Although Panama has not formally joined 
the Central American region, its GNP increased 5.9 percent while 
unemployment declined to 13.9 percent in 1993. (Panama City EL 
PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 1 Jun 94 p 4B) 
  According to a press release issued by the Israeli Embassy 
in 
Panama: "Israeli exports enjoyed a successful year in 1993. 
Israel's international sales increased 11 percent, while in 
Latin America, they rose 22 percent." Meanwhile, the increase 
in Israeli exports to Panama was even higher, growing some 52 
percent in just one year. (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in 
Spanish 1 Jun 94 p 4B) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

