<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Exporters Chamber President Views Decrease in Exports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Exporters Chamber President Views Decrease in Exports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0806023194 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2054 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0806023194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 7 Jun (NA) -- Daniel Brunella, 
president of the Chamber of Exporters, today admitted his 
concern over the fact that during the first 4 months of the year 
exports grew by only 4 percent, and demanded "very urgent and 
concrete" measures to achieve a significant increase in sales 
abroad. 
  The businessman believes that an increase in imports cannot 
be avoided because they are caused by the overall growth of the 
economy, but he considers that it is necessary to adopt measures 
so that the government "can achieve the highly touted objective 
of increasing exports." 
  The trade deficit amounted to $2.404 billion during the 
first 
4 months of the year, 378 percent greater than in the same 
period in 1993. 
  Brunella maintained that financing exports, and granting 
loans with an interest rate equal to that in competitor 
countries, are the problems that have to be resolved. 
  Finally, the businessman indicated that "the labor laws must 
be modified to create new job sources and achieve once and for 
all an efficient system of temporary admission." 

</TEXT>

