<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Seeks U.S. Support To Fight Corruption </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Seeks U.S. Support To Fight Corruption </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0706222494 Caracas EL GLOBO in Spanish 4 Jun 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> PA0706222494 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas EL GLOBO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Interior Minister Ramon Escovar Salom has asked 
Strobe Talbott, U.S. assistant secretary of state, for his 
country's assistance in fighting corruption, given this struggle 
cannot be waged within the limits of Venezuela alone and 
requires the support of major countries to efficiently combat 
it. Corruption at home sometimes has implications abroad, the 
official has said. 
  Will the extradition of those who have committed offenses be 
discussed? a reporter asked. It is still too early to talk 
about that, but I congratulate you for your imagination, Escovar 
replied during the departure of the U.S. retinue of top 
officials comprising Joan Spero, assistant secretary of state 
for economic affairs, and Alexander Watson, assistant secretary 
of state for inter-American affairs, and Ambassador Jeffrey 
Davidow. 
  The interior minister also discussed with them certain 
topics 
related to the problem of the governability of Venezuela and 
Latin America, because in Venezuela, in his words, we have a 
demonstration of what an ungovernable democracy is. "I told them 
that we did not have an economic crisis in Venezuela but, 
rather, the floundering of institutions, the floundering of 
governability, and that is the challenge this government is 
facing." 
  Increasing cooperation with the United States is 
indispensable. We face common challenges, Escovar said, 
regarding the defense of democracy, in addition to something 
that is very important: the need for major countries' 
cooperation in fighting corruption. We need international 
cooperation, because we want to chase certain crimes of 
corruption out from Venezuelan borders, hence the support we are 
requesting from the international community. 
  U.S. official Talbott talked to reporters about the positive 
results of the meeting with the interior minister. [passage 
omitted]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

