<H3> <TI>   Deadline for Compliance With Recommendations Set </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deadline for Compliance With Recommendations Set </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806235294 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0806235294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jaime Guerrero from the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Only 50 percent of the recommendations issued by the 
National Human Rights Committee [CNDH] are in compliance. In 
light of this situation, President Salinas set a 30-day deadline 
for the government and organizations to comply with the 
recommendations. Here is a report by Jaime Guerrero: 
  [Begin recording] [Guerrero] The leading problem the CNDH 
faces is that of partial compliance with its recommendations, 
but a statement issued today at Los Pinos presidential residence 
could be interpreted as a warning. The federal government might 
apply sanctions against those who do not fully comply with CNDH 
recommendations. 
  Several governors might be among those penalized. Jorge 
Madrazo has submitted his report. Madrazo said that during the 
past four years, the CNDH issued 796 recommendations, of which 
51 percent were in partial compliance. As a result, a 30-day 
deadline was established for state governments and organizations 
to comply with CNDH recommendations. President Salinas has said 
the law will be applied to its fullest extent. 
  [Salinas] I urge state governors to join this national 
effort 
with a greater enthusiasm, and I urge the CNDH president to 
disclose, under a strict time limit, a new public report on the 
results of compliance with the recommendations. The last 
results have been referred here as negligent noncompliance. 
  [Guerrero] During the past year, the CNDH received 
approximately 9,000 complaints, of which human rights violations 
in prisons, abuse of authority, and arbitrary arrests head the 
list. Torture reportedly ranks 10th on the long list of 
violations nationwide. 
  [Madrazo] In the fight against torture, we have not had the 
resolute support of all governors or all judges. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

