<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Deny Imposing `Sieges' in Chiapas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Armed Forces Deny Imposing `Sieges' in Chiapas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806222894 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0346 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0806222894 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 7 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- Today, the Mexican 
Armed Forces stated they are conducting searches in Chiapas to 
prevent the traffic of weapons and explosives, denying media 
reports they had imposed "sieges" in that southeastern state. 
  "Searches are being conducted at the military checkpoints 
established in the area with the sole purpose of preventing the 
trafficking of weapons and explosives toward the conflict area," 
the National Secretariat of Defense stated. 
  The Armed Forces issued a communique to deny media reports 
they had imposed "restrictions," "sieges," and "quarantines" in 
an area where the conflict that began on 1 January is being 
resolved. 
  The Zapatist National Liberation Army concluded the first 
phase of a reconciliation dialogue with Manuel Camacho Solis, 
commissioner for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas, on 1 March. 
  The dialogue took place amid a virtual truce in San 
Cristobal 
de las Casas, 200 km southeast of Mexico City, following the 
unilateral cease-fire ordered by President Carlos Salinas de 
Gortari on 12 January. 
  The communique revealed that "the National Secretariat of 
Defense stated categorically" that since the unilateral 
cease-fire, the Armed Forces "have and will continue to 
facilitate" the transit of residents, goods, and medical 
attention. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

