<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lula Favors Creating National Public TV Network </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lula Favors Creating National Public TV Network </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0906032694 Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO in Portuguese 2229 GMT 
8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0906032694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cachoeiro de Itapemirim, Espirito Santo, 8 Jun (AE) 
-- If elected president, PT [Workers Party] candidate Luiz 
Inacio Lula da Silva wants to create a public television channel 
to counterbalance the "monopoly of the great private 
broadcasting companies." Today he defended the creation of a 
public broadcasting company reaching from "Oiapoque [Amapa 
State] to Chui [Rio Grande do Sul State]," and asked, referring 
to the owners of the television networks: "How is it that one 
citizen alone can speak to 80 million Brazilians?" 
  Lula mentioned the "TV Cultura" station of Sao Paulo as an 
ideal model for the new public station. "I want a television 
channel transmitting serious reports to counterbalance the large 
television networks, a channel that will broadcast something 
more than commercial programs." 
  The PT candidate criticized the excessive violence shown on 
television, and said that in Brazil 90 percent of the media is 
in the hands of nine families. He also criticized the rules 
used to grant television station licenses. "Every town in the 
interior has a former deputy, a former governor, who owns a 
radio or television channel," he complained. 
  Lula guarantees that the new television channel -- which 
would be created by reformulating TV Educativa -- would not be 
just another public television station serving merely to 
increase the federal government's payroll. "I want to take 
advantage of what already exists in several states, and transmit 
a uniform national programming," he said. 

</TEXT>

