<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Vows Not To Approve New Amnesty Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Vows Not To Approve New Amnesty Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0806114494 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1726 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0806114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santiago, 7 Jun (AFP-NA) -- Official sources said on 
7 June that Chilean President Eduardo Frei will not approve any 
"new amnesty law" to liberate military officers accused of 
violating human rights under the Augusto Pinochet regime. 
  More than 500 cases of assassination, kidnapping, and the 
disappearance of nearly 1,000 individuals who opposed Pinochet 
-- whose regime extended from 1973 to 1990 -- were filed in 
court during the four years of Patricio Aylwin's administration, 
who was succeeded by Eduardo Frei. 
  "We support the principle that those found responsible by 
the 
courts should be punished," Secretary General of Government 
Victor Manuel Rebolledo said. 
  "A new amnesty law has not been contemplated," Rebolledo 
added, referring to the amnesty law promulgated by Pinochet in 
April 1978 freeing many of his agents from facing trials for 
crimes committed before that date. 
  One of those crimes was the assassination of former Foreign 
Minister Orlando Letelier, who was killed by a bomb that 
exploded under his car in downtown Washington on 21 September 
1976. 
  On 3 June, the Supreme Court refused to apply the amnesty 
law 
to absolve two of the main culprits in that crime, former 
intelligence chief General Manuel Contreras and Brigadier Pedro 
Espinoza, who were sentenced by a lower court to seven years in 
prison. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

