<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   OAS Assembly Meeting Continues 8 Jun in Brazil </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS Assembly Meeting Continues 8 Jun in Brazil </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Baena Soares Urges Compliance With Embargo </H4>

<F P=102> PY0806145394 Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network in 
Portuguese 1000 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0806145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Radio Nacional da Amazonia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Antonia Marcia Valle from Belem, Para State] </F>
  [Text] Commercial flights to Haiti of the countries of the 
American continent will be canceled, the bank accounts of the 
military officers who ousted President Jean-Bertrand Aristide 
will be frozen, and the commercial and financial transactions 
with Haiti will be suspended. These measures are part of the 
resolution approved on 7 June by the OAS Assembly. They 
reinforce the economic blockade already imposed on the 
dictatorial Haitian regime. Their objective is to force the 
coupist military officers to leave power. 
  In OAS Secretary General Ambassador Baena Soares' opinion, 
these measures can only be effective if all countries comply 
with them. Baena Soares pointed out that these same sanctions 
already have been approved by the OAS five times: 
  [Begin Baena Soares recording] All that is missing is 
compliance with what has been approved. Sanctions, as the United 
Nations calls them, and measures, as the OAS calls them, can be 
effective, but only if they are complied with. [end recording] 
  The blockade of Haiti was reinforced after the plenary 
session listened to a report by the UN and OAS representative 
for Haiti, (Collin Granderson). He reported on murdered and 
missing people, and on an escalation of raping of wives, 
mothers, daughters, and sisters of militants who defend 
democracy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

