<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Guard Creates Radio Station </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidential Guard Creates Radio Station </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0806214694 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0806214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The Army is competing with Santa Fe de Bogota radio 
stations that broadcast to young audiences. Radio station S5.9, 
created and run by soldiers of the Presidential Guard Battalion, 
is on the air beginning today. 
  The Presidential Guard Battalion no longer has to wake up to 
the sounds of reveille only. The soldiers now wake up to music 
played on 88.3 MHz, a frequency that identifies S5.9, a military 
radio station. 
  [Begin radio announcer Juan Carlos Ramirez recording] All of 
the equipment came from the Presidential Guard Battalion. In 
general, everyone ranging from colonels to captains contributed, 
including the soldiers. It all began when the soldiers started 
bringing their records. They brought their drawings representing 
the radio station. They brought microphones and equipment. The 
console came from the Presidential Guard Battalion. [end 
recording] 
  The radio station will reach all residents of Santa Fe de 
Bogota with variety shows, such as the War Tank, and the 
reveille beginning today. They hope to get civilians to listen 
to the radio station as well; this does not mean the radio 
station will ease up on military discipline. Here is what the 
colonel had to say: 
  [Begin unidentified speaker recording] Training is stronger 
now, but it is accompanied by psychology. These men are being 
trained so that when they finish their military career they can 
work in a radio or television station. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

