<H3> <TI>   OAS Meeting Views Haiti Sanctions, Other Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OAS Meeting Views Haiti Sanctions, Other Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Baena Soares Lauds `Positive' Results </H4>

<F P=102> PY1006021594 Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO in Portuguese 2133 GMT 
9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1006021594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Jose Carlos Santana] </F>
  [Excerpts] Belem, 9 Jun (AE) -- The 24th OAS General 
Assembly will close here on 10 June. The 34 OAS member states 
have described its results as positive and quite significant, 
especially in the area of human rights. OAS Secretary General 
Joao Baena Soares characterized the approval of an 
inter-American convention to prevent, punish, and eradicate the 
use of violence against women -- which was already signed by 
five countries, Brazil included -- and of an inter-American 
convention on the forcible disappearance of people, namely 
political activists, as "extremely significant for the future of 
the continent." [passage omitted] 
  In addition to the above two conventions, Baena Soares also 
mentioned the adoption of a resolution proposing greater 
cooperation for hemispheric security and limiting the 
proliferation of instruments of war, a proposal to create an 
inter-American defense board, and another proposal containing 
measures to improve the inter-American program to preserve the 
environment. 
  Baena Soares said: "I could not have asked for better and 
more significant results at the Belem meeting." He added: "The 
decisions made here are proof that the OAS is increasingly 
becoming a forum in which all countries in the hemisphere can 
discuss political and economic issues and other types of issues 
as well." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
